                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>&#34;Jerusalem &#40;Holy City&#41; the Glory of all Lands.&#34;¬ù<lb/>
                Alfred A. Marcus&#44;<lb/>
                Diamond Merchant and Importer&#44;<lb/>
                Purchaser of Real Estate &#40;Landed Property&#41;&#44;<lb/>
                A Large Stock of Diamonds&#44; Rough and Polished&#44; also Precious<lb/>
                Stones in every variety&#44; always on hand&#44;<lb/>
                Box 3927&#44; Equitable Safe Deposit Vaults&#44; 67 Milk Street &#40;directly opposite the Post&#45;Office&#41;.<lb/>
                Residence&#44; 127 Dartmouth Street.<lb/>
                No business will be transacted or interviews had on the Jewish Sabbath&#44; from one hour before<lb/>
                sunset on Friday until one hour after sunset on Saturday&#44; or on the Jewish<lb/>
                Festivals&#44; and no letters will be opened on those days.<lb/></p>
            <p>Boston&#44;	A.M. 564<lb/></p>

            <p>Boston Heshvan 18<hi rend="sup">th</hi> A.M. 5643<lb/>
                Rev S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours of the 15<hi rend="sup">th</hi> recd. &#38; accept<lb/> our most grateful thanks for your translation<lb/> &#38; corrections. I hope yet one day with the<lb/> Almighty&#39;s blessing to be able to vis&#91;i&#93;t your City<lb/> &#38; then have our desired personal acquaintance<lb/> regarding your remain&#91;in&#93;g in Philadelphia<lb/> at your post more honor to you. If I am<lb/> not troubling you <sic>to</sic> much would you most<lb/> kindly correct the English Copy herewith<lb/> sent &#38; return it me for the printers.<lb/> Enclosed is a letter I rec<hi rend="sup">d</hi>. from Gen<hi rend="sup">l</hi><lb/> Hancock . after reading would you most<lb/> kindly return it&#91;.&#93; my correspondence with<lb/> him extends some time back&#91;.&#93; he is a most<lb/> noble man&#44; &#38; a great lover of our orthodox<lb/> <sic>principals</sic> &#38; I thought a personal<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>acquaintance with him would please you<lb/> &#38; give a better opi&#91;ni&#93;on of our Rabbi than<lb/>other he has most <sic>unfortunally</sic> <sic>meet</sic>&#44; &#38;<lb/> through their hearing of my correspondence<lb/> have taken great advantage of me one in<lb/> particular a so called Revd Mr Guttaheim&#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> or some such name.<lb/></p>
                <p>With the very Kindest regards in which<lb/> Mrs Marcus daughter &#38; son join<lb/> Remain as ever<lb/></p>
                <p>Yours Most Faithfully<lb/>
                Alfred A. Marcus<lb/></p>
        </body>
